However, please note that Open Processing sketches are designed for creative coding and are typically written in the Processing language, also known as p5.js or Java Mode. They are not suitable for directly running or parsing HTML and JavaScript.

To achieve your goal in Java Mode, I would recommend using a Java IDE (like Eclipse or IntelliJ IDEA) and using the `jsoup` library to parse HTML and extract elements. Here's an example of how you could achieve this in Java:

```java
import org.jsoup.Jsoup;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Document;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Element;
import org.jsoup.select.Elements;

public class InputDivElementExtractor {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    // Your HTML code
    String html = "<!DOCTYPE html>"
        + "<html>"
        + "<body>"
        + "<div>"
        + "<input type='button' value='Click Me'>"
        + "<input type='radio' name='choice'>"
        + "<input type='text'>"
        + "<input type='checkbox'>"
        + "</div>"
        + "</body>"
        + "</html>";

    // Parse the HTML using jsoup
    Document document = Jsoup.parse(html);

    // Find input elements
    Elements inputs = document.select("input");

    // Iterate over the input elements, extracting the ones that are user inputs
    for (Element input : inputs) {
      String type = input.attr("type");
      if ("button".equalsIgnoreCase(type)
          || "radio".equalsIgnoreCase(type)
          || "text".equalsIgnoreCase(type)
          || "checkbox".equalsIgnoreCase(type)) {
        System.out.println("Found input element: " + input);
      }
    }
  }
}
```

To run this code, you would need to include the jsoup library (available at https://jsoup.org/) in your Java project.

If you prefer working with a Processing sketch, you can use the `loadStrings()` function to load an HTML file from the project folder and then parse it using `Jsoup`. Please refer to the Processing documentation for more details on how to load files: https://processing.org/reference/loadStrings_.html

