To accomplish this, you can use JavaScript's querySelectorAll to select all elements with `aria-name="testdiv"` and then use a combination of recursion and checking `aria-label` to find the nested elements with `aria-label="hello"`. Here's a working example:

HTML:
```html
<div aria-name="testdiv">
  <div>
    <div aria-label="hello">Example 1</div>
  </div>
</div>
<div aria-name="testdiv">
  <div>
    <div aria-label="other">Example 2</div>
  </div>
</div>
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
function findElementsWithAriaLabel(element, label) {
  if (element.getAttribute("aria-label") === label) {
    return [element];
  }

  let matches = [];
  for (let child of element.children) {
    matches.push(...findElementsWithAriaLabel(child, label));
  }
  return matches;
}

function filterTestDivsWithNestedAriaLabelHello() {
  const testDivs = document.querySelectorAll('[aria-name="testdiv"]');
  const filteredDivs = [];

  for (let div of testDivs) {
    const helloElements = findElementsWithAriaLabel(div, "hello");
    if (helloElements.length > 0) {
      filteredDivs.push(div);
    }
  }

  return filteredDivs;
}

console.log(filterTestDivsWithNestedAriaLabelHello());
```

In this example, the `filterTestDivsWithNestedAriaLabelHello()` function will return an array of all the elements with `aria-name="testdiv"` that have a nested element with `aria-label="hello"`.
